Even though his political enemies used that title to brand him as evil.
That, btw, is why Vlad was never ashamed to call himself Dracula, because it referred to a very elite title he inherited from his father.
The final "a" is diminutive, so Dracula means "son of the dragon". But also can take on a malevolent connotation as "son of the devil".
Unfortunately, in Romanian "Dracul" means both dragon and devil, and dragons were popularly associated with the devil (think St George).
This is why when he returned to Romania (actually Wallachia) the local nobles called him "Dracul" or "the dragon".
He was inducted into the knightly Order of the Dragon, which Sigismund founded to fight the Hussites and other heretics.
Vlad's father (also Vlad) lived many years at the court of the Holy Roman Emperor Sigismund I.
